Of course finding the assets is only part of the problem... finding the owner of the asset so you can ask them to update can be harder (assuming the owner still works at the org). Best advice? If you can‚Äôt find an owner ‚Äúsoon‚Äù then quarantine; quickest way to flush the owner out.

@randomlick @jeremiahg Quarantine has the same effect and it‚Äôs often easier than shutting a system down. Also, in my experience, only very rarely do you find a system doing something important and it doesn‚Äôt have an owner or an owner is not easily discoverable, fortunately :)

@mattjay @jeremiahg Assuming a well established scanning program the answer to the last part would be it would have been knocked over long ago and the owner would complain if you knocked it over again, and again.... To the first part (cont)

@mattjay @jeremiahg We‚Äôll typically exploit a system after all other avenues (and there are many) of have been exhausted a peruse the file system for clues to who the owner is or was and what role the system plays. If that‚Äôs fruitless it goes to quarantine then decommission.

@SushiDude @4Dgifts @ryanaraine Yep, obscurity as a concept isn‚Äôt solely the preserve of a mechanism‚Äôs or algorithm‚Äôs details.

@4Dgifts @ryanaraine Any measure that can by brute forced or guessed is an obscurity measure. As such an ACL, file or network is not. We both agree changing a default port is an obscurity measure, right? By that logic, changing a default password (let‚Äôs say to 12345) is also an obscurity measure.
@4Dgifts @ryanaraine And if we agree that‚Äôs an obscurity measure then they all are; what you call diversity is equally obscurity.

@4Dgifts @ryanaraine No, I disagree. If there‚Äôs something I know and you don‚Äôt it‚Äôs obscure to you. A changed port is the same - it‚Äôs just easier for you to brute force than brute forcing a password ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

@4Dgifts @ryanaraine Any mitigation where the target knows something the attacker does not: ASLR, stack canary, password, crypto key... all these are at heart obscurity. The question becomes how hard is it to guess/discover the secret (1/2)

@4Dgifts @ryanaraine A changed default TCP port has the same principle at heart but it‚Äôs easy to discover so is an example of when an obscurity measure isn‚Äôt strong; but I tell you what, it‚Äôs certainly better than leaving it as default. Ask 99% of worms :)
@ryanaraine @4Dgifts Obscurity/opaqueness lies at the heart of many successful mitigations ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è
